# TÜİK Forecasting Project

## 1. Project Overview
The purpose of this project is to develop a fully reproducible time series forecasting model using R. It aims to predict the next-period value for Lignite Marketable Production in Turkey by dynamically fetching data directly from the TÜİK Data Portal and evaluating ten distinct forecasting methods.

## 2. Data Source and TÜİK Connection
The data were accessed directly from the TÜİK Data Portal using the `tuikr` R package, strictly avoiding any manual downloads.
- TÜİK data set name: Solid Fuels Statistics
- TÜİK theme/category: Energy (5)
- TÜİK table name: Solid Fuels Production and Deliveries
- TÜİK dataflow ID: 5
- Selected variable: Lignite Marketable Production (Tonnes)
- Data frequency: Monthly
- Time coverage: 2020-01 to 2026-01
- Latest available observation: 2026-01
- Forecast target period: 2026-02
- Date of data access: June 2026
- R package used for data access: `tuikr`
- Package source: https://github.com/emraher/tuikr

## 3. Research Objective
The variable being forecasted is Lignite Marketable Production. This variable is highly meaningful as lignite is a critical domestic energy resource in Turkey. Forecasting its production provides valuable insights into the stability of the energy supply chain, thermal power plant operations, and macroeconomic energy planning.

## 4. Use of TÜİK Data in R
The TÜİK data imported through `tuikr` were used in R for forecasting via a fully automated pipeline. Absolutely no manually prepared, manually edited, or newly created data set was used.
- selected variable: Lignite Marketable Production (Tonnes)
- time or period variable: Year and Month (Monthly Index)
- data frequency: Monthly (Frequency = 12)
- latest available observation: 2026-01
- forecast target period: 2026-02
- any R-based filtering or formatting required for the analysis: The raw matrix was cleaned dynamically using `dplyr` and regex (`grepl`). Empty cells, merged headers, and Turkish characters were standardized, and the cleaned numeric values were converted into a formal time series (`ts`) object.

## 5. Exploratory Time Series Analysis
- trend: Evaluated to observe any long-term structural increases or decreases in domestic production capacity.
- seasonality: Analyzed to capture recurring monthly patterns, typically driven by winter heating demand and industrial cycles.
- cyclical movements if visible: Observed for multi-year fluctuations related to broad economic cycles.
- random variation: Accounted for unpredictable short-term supply chain disruptions or operational halts.
- missing values: Automatically filtered and cleaned within the R pipeline (future unobserved months excluded).
- outliers: Retained as natural components of market volatility without manual tampering.

## 6. Forecasting Methods Applied
The following methods were applied and evaluated in the project:
- Naïve Forecasting: Applicable as a baseline assuming the next period equals the most recent observation.
- Moving Average: Applicable for smoothing out random short-term variations (using a 12-month window).
- Weighted Moving Average: Applicable to assign higher importance to recent production months.
- Exponential Smoothing: Applicable for data blocks without dominant trends or seasonality.
- Trend-Adjusted Exponential Smoothing: Applicable for capturing and projecting linear trends.
- Linear Trend Projection: Applicable to model the long-term deterministic trajectory.
- Seasonal Indices: Highly applicable to isolate and forecast inherent monthly seasonality.
- Additive Decomposition: Applicable assuming seasonal variations are constant regardless of the trend level.
- Multiplicative Decomposition: Applicable assuming seasonal variations scale proportionally with the trend.
- Regression with Trend and Seasonal Dummy Variables: Applicable for simultaneously modeling both the linear time effect and specific monthly factors.

## 7. Forecast Accuracy Comparison
The project automatically evaluates all models and generates an accuracy table containing:
- Bias / Mean Error
- MAD
- MSE
- MAPE
- RSFE
- Tracking Signal
*(Note: The computed results are exported dynamically to outputs/tables/accuracy_comparison.csv)*

## 8. Selection of the Superior Method
The superior method is selected automatically by the R script based on the lowest **MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error)**. This ensures the choice is mathematically justified and represents the model with the lowest relative error proportion, making it highly suitable for the observed data structure.

## 9. Final Next-Period Forecast
The final forecast parameters are extracted automatically from the superior model:
- selected superior method: (Auto-determined by the script based on lowest MAPE)
- date of data access: June 2026
- latest available TÜİK observation: 2026-01
- forecast target period: 2026-02
- forecasted value: (Dynamically calculated and exported to outputs/tables/final_forecast.csv)

## 10. Interpretation of Results
The selected model projects the expected Lignite Marketable Production volume for the upcoming target period. In plain language, this figure represents the data-driven expectation of domestic coal output, providing a quantitative basis for short-term energy sector decisions.

## 11. Limitations
The analysis is subject to several potential limitations:
- short time series
- structural breaks
- economic shocks
- data revisions
- weak seasonality
- high volatility
- limited explanatory variables

## 12. Reproducibility
Another user can easily reproduce this project by downloading the repository and executing the main `forecasting_project_1.Rmd` file in RStudio. The script will automatically contact the TÜİK API, bypass dynamic connection issues using `httr::GET`, parse the raw data, execute all 10 forecasting models, and re-generate the output files locally without any manual intervention.

## 13. Repository Structure
- `R/`: Contains modular R scripts (`data_import.R`, `forecasting_methods.R`, etc.).
- `outputs/tables/`: Auto-generated tables (`accuracy_comparison.csv`, `final_forecast.csv`).
- `outputs/figures/`: Auto-generated visualization plots for each model.
- `forecasting_project_1.Rmd`: The main reproducible R Markdown document.
- `forecasting_project_1.html`: The knitted final output report.
- `renv.lock`: R environment lockfile ensuring package version control.
- `.gitignore`: Specifies intentionally untracked files to keep the repository clean.

